[right side of page]:

About a blacksmith forge!
No indeed -
But about a little flowr
? ? Autumns with a bor??

Please take heed.

I walked in the timber
With pigs without much?

What a pest!

But it always is the way
Whatever you may say

At the West!

Dry leaves were raithy?
Round the little nesllry?
Keeping? ?
I thought I would plant?
? unclear

With much care

Pond - Shepherd, Smith

unclear Appleton 1807-19
Allen resigned in 1839 -

Sept
Wednesday 22

We left the Burial Grounds this morning and traversed the streets until past four  I thought the Streets unusually unclean But it may be it is because so much business is transacted - it is truly a very busy city - One notices here the great number of Signs in a foreign tongue - unlike cadtenirtus? - We went into a German Church - large and convenit? and substantial and not inelegant - I got tired and sat down in the tract? Depod..ng? and read for a time - Isaac  bought Mary? L.? Duncan and a volume of Coleridge & got me a new bonnet - We came on board the "Golden State" tonight about five - 'tis a

14
fine boat and our home it must be for four or five days -  
Thursday 23 -

Still at Cincinnati Capt. ? Overtises? to go everyday but still we stay - Been reading "Christabel" and Chamber's Miscellany - books came tonight -

Friday -

Really on our way - and delightful indeed it is  I never enjoyed anything more in a steamboat on the river - good company - no seasickness - the lovelinst of scenery  Occasionally pass an ugly vile Cooking distillery were they waste no co? for bread - Steep miles? of the Ohio and Indiana bank, vine clad even to the summit and beautiful swells covered with a luxuriant growth

15
of forest trees with bright green grass underneath - in place of dry leaves and brush & bushes - cho? & th..? splendid dwellings peer at us from the lofty mill tops and little modest cottages nestle among the trees - Kentucky side is beautiful extremely - How sad that man should foully blot what God has made so fair -  The forests here seen? to me? perfectly enchanting - Large trees with great spreading branches and plenty of room for them to grow in  no underbrush but all smooth and grassy beneath  Jack Frost has begun to paint

16
The  leaves of some of them but most are still fresh and green. Sometimes instead of high banks we pass level bottom lands with great flocks of sheep now and then feeding industriously a little back from the river - hordes cattle and pigs too - and they come to drink at the river brink. Occasionally we pass a steamboat and by way of recognition hats and kerchiefs wave and swing -- and then it is pleasant to watch the receding boat till its great black chimneys disappear and the cloud of smoke vanishes. Isaac and I sat on the deck till almost nine o'clock this evening.
Saturday - Sewed this morning. In afternoon passed through Louisville & Portland. Sat in

with the forward part of the boat while we paddled under a bridge through the canal and locks- Lady with a slave come on board tonight. 
Sabbath Isaac and I sat in our state room almost all day read "Who are the Happy" and Mary L Duncan. In evening wrote some to George.
Monday sat on guard and sewed Isaac read to me from Annual of Science Dis. went on deck while we stopped at Cairo- ate a papaw - I did not like its outward appearance but it was quite comfortable to the taste - In the evening we made ready our luggage - no lack of commodities to fill all the trunks, valises, carpet bags. wrote some to siblings & George

- Tuesday 28 up this morning before three to be ready to stop by Willards Landing - from whence we go to Jonesboro - O such a place such filthy looking people such heads on the children - branching out in all directions

18
Wednesday

Reached Jonesboro about 2 o'clock yesterday - rode from the landing in a long wagon with four or five other passengers. Jonesboro is really quite a pleasant place - I think I would be very contented here  A Widow Cady, Mrs. Greeman? - would like to board us - but probably we shall not stay - Most of the people here say which in place of what - We have quite a company at table and I the only female -  ?aint? to ride this forenoon with Mr & Mrs Ashley - They sent over an invitation quite lovly this morning.  Mr Y? has a nice comfortable four wheel vehicle and there are a pair of mules in the village that go finely in a carriage - It seemed strange to be drawn by mules but I liked them? They are the handsomest

19
I ever saw. We stopped at an orchard of Persimons - a kind of fruit resembling plums in size and appro??]] sweeter and richer - They stay on the tree until winter improving all the while.
Thursday 30 - Wrote to E. Knapp this forenoon - Afternoon sat down to hem table cover and Mrs. Ashley came - made a short call and asked me to go home with her - I did, and came back just in season for supper - She has a pretty little girl - she had ?oved a monster apple for me wh. grew in their yard - Quite a nice looking house they have - In the evening a lady came in to hear the melodian - She lives next

20
door and had heard it from her room - I was pleased with her appearance - I imagine there are a number of very pleasant families in the village. The people have been quite affected with small pox but the last case had recovered before we came -
Saturday - At home all day - in my room  Isaac  with me nearly all the time - wrote some to Maine  mother & some to Dunbarton mother - We went to walk at night -discussed on the way distillers and walnuts - the merits & demerits of green corn as an article of food - Called a moment at Mrs. Ashleys

21
Sabbath - Oct 3 - We read together, aloud eight chapters in Isaiah and then prepared us for meeting - We listened to a very comfortable discourse fr. Mr. Phillips at the Baptist Chh. The poor man has lost one child of small pox and now another is not expected to live  A young man who worked in a tailors shop in this building was this norn. found dead in his bed - probably from a fit. Sabbath afternoon here is the universal time for calling  but we shall not be troubled for people here know Isaac's habits? too well to venture here - Can not help thinking some

22
about home this day - blessing be upon them all, today and evermore - The same dear Father watches over us and them -
Monday. Oct 4 - Made my room tidy - wrote home to send by today mail - Mended (pants and suspender)  Ellen? brought me a very large nicely baked sweet potatoe - it looked good enough to eat - At night went in to Mrs Parks - and Mrs Brooks and I went to walk - Isaac read Casmod? in evening -
Tuesday - Isaac  gone all day - Thought I should be very lonely but the forenoon was all gone before I had time to think - Mrs. Parks & Mrs Brooks

23
came just as I had finished rubbing and scraping and washing to get-off the mud from my shoes - the result of last evening's walk - I played to them but I felt bad for it seemed as if nothing went right - Then before they went Mrs-Ashley and Mrs Back append? my room w?uld? not stretch to enclose so many so we went down stairs to the parlor. Came up again to play - but O dear me - what would they think! It would not go right at all - and then afterwards I found Mrs Ashley used to play piano and that Mrs. B. Played the melodian!  Alone all the afternoon -   Isaac  came

24
just after tea and we went over to Mr. Willard - seems quite like East, nice house piano, double parlors &c - very pleasant people neither much intellectual - Mr W. knew nothing of "Uncle Tom's Cabin" - no sort of comprehension what it could be. Isaac  went to the meeting of the "Sons" after we came home. I sat with Mrs. Riley.
- Wednesday - Very warm - Isaac home most of forenoon - Letter came from Miss N. Good letter - full of good -  Went to walk about four  Isaac  with me -
Thursday - Took my sewing about 1/2 past nine and went over to Mrs. Ashley's - had nuts &c. Went up into the office - very pleasant room - Isaac  left work and came home with me. Spect

25
It's naughty to want him too. After dinner Mrs Brooks came over. I played - When we went into Dr. Parks - while she got ready to go walking - Saw Dr. P.  Gre?ne? ? taking a sister on the lounge and looked somewhat frizzled -  We had a fine walk away to the woods and hills and gathered a boquet of the last Autumn flowers Solidago, Aster, purple & white, Lobelia, Gerardia, and bright colored leaves - In the dear little Lucy vase they look quite beautiful -  In the evening Mrs Ashly & children and Miss Culver came in
Friday Oct. 8. Dark rainy morning but bright before dinner - Sewed and read in A.M. At noon Mary washed our room. This afternoon read some - cut out & hemmed

26
a lace cap to send home to my mother - Isaac      has been trying a long while to buy a nag but no success as yet - Mr. Ashly told him tonight to get a gentle one and then we would all go riding Mrs Ashly behind him and my own self behind Isaac  - we all thought it would be just the thing - In evening Mrs. Brooks came - bringing a very jewel of a boquet wh. made the little wild wood treasures of yesterday begin to shrink away - and look brown  But the ??dest? little darling need never be troubled - even in presence of the dignified Dahlia and beautiful queen Rosa - But the Dahlias & the Roses do look perfect

27
in beauty tonight as the lamp light falls on them - twined? with mist? the loving myrtle and cedar & honeysuckle and pretty wax strawberries  O the flowers! What a charm they throw round? life - "Gods smiles" they are and they make all Nature glad    Mary said this morning sent Mrs Squires? was getting right smart again, but she was mighty weak yet
Saturday - read Lake Lupin? and sewed on mother's cap in forenoon - After dinner Isaac  went to the office and got the Living Age - this unclear fun..? of reading for us and  unclear good reading beside - Went over to Mrs Parks -

28
my sewing for an hour- Made some delicious gingerbread - it tasted so good for I have had none since we left home - Called too on Miss Culver - got the Report of N.P.E. &c. It was cold at night and we went down and sat by the fire - Therm. 46 [degrees] - Two days before up to 82 [degrees] & 86 [degrees] -
Sabbath - Quietly at home today - reading Report? N.P.S.S. and Mary L Duncan beside Bible - no meeting in town till evening - Went to hear ?dd? Father Krach in Evening or rather "after night" as the people here call it - We have no afternoon. The evening and the morning make the days as in the

29
years before the flood - It is evening after dinner. After supper it is "after night" I do like the old German he is so good and every syllable seems coming directly from his heart of hearts - None can help liking him he is so ardent & earnest  Even those who care not for religious reverence Gather? Krach and turn? his pity?-true heart? This noble voice is deep and full but soft and melodious so much so that the hymn hardly needs to be sung after he has read it - unclear he was selecting hymns tonight he said in his meed fatherly tone slowly as he always speaks - sing something friends. They sung Jesus I my cross have

30
taken" to the tune Greenville, and when it ended, he was ready to read the hymn he had selected, wh. he did and then it was sung by the Cong. lined off to them after the manner of the older time - Then came the prayer, then old man stretched forth his hands and said Please arise, and then followed one of the most deeply impr..unclear prayers I ever heard - His text was the " Master is come and calleth for thee" - I really enjoyed the meeting exceedingly - The slight German brogue rather added to the interest - called W as if it were V When quoting scripture it is perfectly evident he has it

31
from a German Edition of Bible. Same ideas the Eng. gr?n? but the expression varies -
Monday - 11 Oct  Isaac  gone today - started off to be away three or four days - rumaging? or rearranging? trunks almost all the morning and putting our goods in a more comatable? condition - When I went to dinner Mrs Levinnth? said I looked lonely - because the seat by my side was vacant - I felt a little so - but they all tried to minister to my necessities - Mr L - Mrs ? Mr Ashly - I reckon I'll not want for any of the good things of the table for lack of helping hands - Mrs. A. brought me some beautiful cedar sprigs and "blackbrier so I'll have a boquet all winter long

32
finished Achsah letter after dinner - began it yesterday eve. How strange not to see Isaac  when evening comes - day passed very comfortably but it does seem lonely now
Tuesday - gone is the day and evening too, before I know it - In the morning I was very  ? reading Suoeri.?, French Testa?d? &c playing?, sewing, cutting out a cap for Mrs. Kelly - Afternoon I sewed till Mrs. Ashly called for me to go to Mrs. Freeman (1/2 2) - had a nice walk down and plesent visit with Mrs. Freeman & Bach  Mrs Ashlys children were there Mr S & Mr B there to tea - - I wouldn't give my Isaac  for ten thousand Bucks, no not I. They all walked home

with me and called unclear moment. We heard Mrs B. play the guitar very prettily this eve - the house girls have been up hearing the Melodian - Mrs Brooks in too a long while - Five days are gone now - This has been a cold one - I went down by the fire all day - Hope Isaac  will buy a blanket, to wrap about his thin garments - Never even took an extra coat  Naughty girl I, not to ask him too  Two ladies called Mrs Condin & Walker
Wednesday - 13 - Finished Superior and went to walk alone. Wrote three pages to Lucy before Dinner and finished after Din. Mary Ashly came over to invite me to go nutting with her mother &

34
Ellen Dougherty - gone till after Suppertime - children went too - we had a fine walk but the thievish pigs had found the nuts before us  We must have found about 1/2 doz. apiece - got some acorns, one hazel nut, one apple & one cluster little grapes - wish? I had no matter how many grapes, for they are just the thing - Irishman went to the P.O. for me, and found a letter from dear home - dearest Mother - How glad I am she is not sick - Who so blessed as I - I am a happy child but I'll be happier still tomorrow when somebody comes - Blessings be with him

35
wherever he be.
Thursday -14 - Isaac came a little past noon - I walked a little distance with him after his dinner and then took sewing in to Dr Parks. He asked about Gen. Pierce.
Friday - sewed on Mrs. Kelseys cap all the forenoon - called on Mrs Walker, Mrs. Condin and Mrs Jenkins, in the afternoon and had a short walk with Isaac just before supper - Mrs. Jenkins glad to see me - did not recognize me at first - told me all about Lockport & ?omer? people   was very sorry we are not to stay here - I regret it too on her account, at least I should like to be near her -

36
Saturday - 16 - Sewed in forenoon  commenced reading "Friends and Fortune" - Afternoon went walking a long way with Mrs. Ashly, Mrs. Freeman, Mrs Buck  Miss Dougherty and Miss Culver  Miss C and I walked together most  I like her much - She came home with me, and stopped to tea, and so did Mrs. Simons whoom we found when we came fr. walking; with Mrs. Kannig - came to call - very pleasant people. Mrs. K. a little deaf - Mrs. S. very lively - from New York. Isaac gone all day -
Sunday 17. Went to hear old Mr Sharp - Mr Albright made remarks too - They both screamed and roared with all their

37
might - {Methodists} Played some afternoon - finished Mary Sund?u?D, Not very well in Evening - went to bed early but talked till past eleven -
18 Monday - wrote home to send in Achsah's letter. Isaac gone - not home to dinner - mended some  Mrs. Brooks came in to get some book marks and bring home some - In afternoon read and worked a little with worsted - at night Isaac went to walk with me - and read to me in the Evening from Cosmos? and "Friends & Fortune" -
19 Tuesday - 19 - Arranged a boqet this morn, and then went into Mr. Narl? & Willards Store - like the Mrs Willard very much - polite and kind - Went into Mrs.

30
Willard's, and unexpectedly decided to take one of her handsome patterns for worsted and work it this winter  Isaac thinks it will be precious time wasted - and it may be he is right - but I do really think it will not be useless - Mrs. N? gave me a ripe fig? just from the tree - It was quite nice. I finished Mrs Ks Cap and completed "Friends and Fortune" - Called on Mrs. Ashly - she is eating at home now, so I am all the lady at table again - I come not when Isaac is with me. He is gone to the meeting of S.T.? this Eve -
Wednesday 20 - Mr. Crosby

39
came today - brought not a letter for us - too bad!
Thursday - We both took Blue Pill {detestable!} last night and are both not exactly well today - but there is some good about it - for me at least - Isaac does not feel well enough to be away so he stays with me - has read almost all day - Just before tea - Mrs Ashly come over to have me go calling with her - I was on the bed, but I arose and dressed and went to Mr Jenkins  Mrs Konings  Mrs Simons & Doughertys - came home later to supper - tired   Sermon? in Evening but

40
I did not go and Isaac only a few minutes - He was not well and it was tiresome - The Baptist Convention for South, ILL. meets here this week - meetings commenced here today -
Friday - Went to chh forenoon & Evening - good sermons. Went walking alone in the morning - had a good time too
Saturday 23 - Company in forenoon - Mary Jenkins - told me abundance of news about Lockport - Afternoon Mrs & Miss Jenkins  Miss Culver & I went to the Big Mill - and came home by the spring that comes out between two rocks - we enjoyed it very exceedingly - the scenery

41
is magnificent - the extreme of wildness and romance  Went to meeting in Evening -  Mr. Phillips very bold against Sabbath breakers Said I will strike of from the list of members of Conv. the name of every brother who leaves on the Sabbath. He hoped no brother would wickedly break the sabbath by traveling  The meetings are to be continued several days of next week   Letters today from Maine {Lucy}  glad enough we were.
Sabbath - bright - beautiful day - O that the prospects of the Spiritual words were as brilliant and glowing as all nature this morning that the beams of the Sun of Righteousns might but illumined

42
illumined the world unclear light and all mankind acknowledge the God of the Sabbath -  Attended chh forenoon & afternoon - remained at home reading & writing in Evening 
Monday - not feeling very well before my room was in order  Miss Culver called, then Mrs Kornig then Mrs. Parks  I finished and mailed a letter to Augusta after they went -  Read Littel in afternoon and went out walking in woods alone - Sat down on a log to read  helped the pigs gather & crack hickory nuts - Isaac home in evening  read "Cosmos".
Tuesday 26 - Advocate came today - I finished letter to Lucy

43
In afternoon sewed on a mantilla for Mrs Kelly -  Rainy, and I could not go out at all. Mended a coat,
Wednesday - rainy today too  Sewing some as yesterday  read "Margaret Smith." In evening Mr. Roots came - said he was the very old Sucker Isaac used to write to me about, last year - Supposed I had had many a laugh over him - he is really a funny old man - Said he had been an apt scholar in L?uccendom? He believed in presence? of Yankay he could talk as the Yankes too but when with the "nations" he could call a pail a bucket or say powerful weak or

44
miserable happy. He says if we go to Du Quoin I shall not even learn the language of the county - He thinks Isaac has been rather a dull scholar - I am glad of it - hope he will continue so,  Sent letters to Lucy & Almeda
Thursday 28. Sewed all the morning. Letter come from Anna - grand good one, and I was so glad to get it - O how good to have sisters - Mary is sick with ague. Rainy today too - what shall I do: I do so need to be out of doors for exercise
Friday - wrote Mother M. Sewed  Mrs Jenkins called & Miss Culver brought boquet - Chrys. Petunia, Pea  Heartsease - Puff  Lady traveller stopped from Vergennes - acquainted at Du

45
Quoin - says two ministers live there - just got a bell - She knows Mrs Keyes where we are to travel - Miss Garnet, an Eastern teacher at Vergennes, is going home this autumn    I called on Mrs Ashly - caught in the rain, but Isaac came with an umbrella -
Saturday. Oct 30. finished Mrs Kelley's Rilley's? mantilla. Glad enough it was wadded and lined in front with green silk - and quilted. Trimmed with broad lace - folds of silk above -  Company in afternoon  Miss Culver  Mrs Brooks - Miss C. talked of school wanted me to tell her how I did for general exercises - said she had trouble in classing - there were so many different ages in her school

46
Sabbath. 31.  Isaac read Independent aloud. We went to hear Father Krach in A M. Not quite so interesting as before. Seemed vague,, and disultory - But just as much melody in his voice as ever. Wrote some home in A.M.  Gave Elvira tracts.
Monday Nov. 1. Sewed and read - went to walk alone in the woods. Sent letter home
Tuesday -2  Worked book mark {Prayer} - hemmed pocket handkerchief  Went in to Dr. Parks & ate nuts - Went with Miss Culver to her Darius for the Evening - Quite a Yankee Company  Ladies all knitting - The Suckers never do such a thing -  Do not know how Miss D. looks
Note: Illinois was known as the "Sucker" State at this time

47
like a good mother - Mrs. Walker her daughter is very pleasant. We expect to go to Du Quoin Thursday - unless more rain comes
Wednesday Nov. 3 Swept our rooms. Mrs Jenkins sent for me to come and see an old Lockport acquaintance Mrs Nellis who is visiting there. I finished Margaret Smiths Iannal? and went there and to Mrs Ashly's & Kannigs. How? pleasant calls - Mrs  S. gave me first rate pie & milk  It did taste good enough. Mrs J. invited us over to tea and we would have gone but I was not well enough. Mrs Walker came in the afternoon and Mrs Buck. Miss Culver was

48
coming after school with four or five young ladies to hear the melodian but I was forced to send them word I could not play  Isaac brought tea & bread for my supper. Miss Culver came in the evening. I gave her "Mary Lundin" - She is a dear good girl.
Thursday. 4- Feel better today, but it rained so hard last night that it is too muddy to ride - car? baggage? started this morn but it begins even now to rain again and it may get a wetting - Letter come from George today. Writes very affectionately and very soberly - I do hope he will

49
be permitted to do good in this world - It seems sad to think how little prospect there is that we will ever be much more together here - but I ought not to be troubled for this, I know - but I do not believe I am as ready to submit to it as he
Friday.  Rainy today too - so we cannot go. Mr. Buck has gone - left his wife for us to take care of & Eva?. It rained very fast - the lightenings flash and the thunder's roar the swarms of mosquitoes Sing and the flies dona?  It is warm as N.E. Summer.  At home the snow flakes were falling long ago. I shall not see the magnificant piles of white snow I an so accustomed to. I shall miss the sleigh riding too and some

50
of the snapping biting cold weather  Read little today - review of Mary of Scotland -
Saturday   How many Autumn days! and how fast they do follow each other - The weeks glide away like minutes  A letter came from Catha - good & kind - She expects to go to South Hadly? this month as Latin Instructress. Very perfectly adapted to it & qualified for it - I shd judge -   We both called on Mrs Grumn? She seemed extremely cordial exceedingly sorry to have us leave 
Sab. Nov 7.  went to here Mr. Phillip  Miss Jenkins & Mrs Nellis called afternoon - first Sabbath  calls we have received, and last too here for we go tomorrow

5
Aug 13 - Friday - Mr. White called - once settled in London - knew father.
Saturday - read Lettice Arnold - knit Blue cotton stockings -
Aug 15 - Sabbath at home - no preaching  read John Bunyan's, Capt Simon - "Henry on Meekness" -
Monday. Dinner at Alinder's  Read Paley's Theology -
Tuesday 17 - Afternoon on the river - good by boat ride - beautiful river! When shall we meet again?
Thursday - Aug 19 - Came to Bangor
Friday - Shopping almost all day - tired enough - Oh how many, many thoughts and

6
how much time we do give to this world - vanity of vanities - how little worth
Saturday 21,  Sewed & read and had fine long talk with Lucy - told me about Miss? E.
Sabbath - Mr. Hyde of Gorde?? & Mr Dunning of Thompson unclear - Rev. 15 -3 {read Morning of day}?  [Note: Revelation 15-3]
Monday 23 Aug. Forenoon at Daguerreotype room for pictures to send to Milo for Lucy, and to have at Dunbarton  Afternoon - at Dr. C? Igood's? having teeth filled unpleasant  Isaac stayed with me all the afternoon. Weary enough at night.
Tuesday. Aug 24 - Dentist's again in forenoon - Annaversariy? in afternoon - heard Rev. Mr. Drummond of Lewiston Falls -
Wednesday - Annaversarius? - Student of the Graduating Class in A.M. Prof. Stowe in P.M. "God's care for the nations" - his theme -

7
Thursday - rainy - In the forenoon Ordination of Mr. C. Pond as Missionary to California   Dentists in Afternoon -
Friday - rainy. Finished at Dentists -
Saturday Aug 28 - Rode to Oldtown through N. Bangor and Grand? Saw Indians - birch canoe's, saw mills rafts?  Called on Mr. Nash? - anxious to have us stop over the Sabbath
Sabbath - Aug 29 -
Monday - Came from Bangor to Brunswick in the "Governor"  rainy and foggy - some sea sick -  "read  Roughing it in the bush" - Reached B. about 11 o'c.
Aug 31. Heard Addresses before Alumni - great collection from all parts of the Union

8
Addreses good - must have been very indeed interesting to the good-voters on account of allusion? to days past.
Sept 3 - remained in Brunswick until Thursday afternoon when we left for Lawrence where we spent the night - Started this morn at half past eight for home - aftr rumaging over considerable port of the town after Dry goods stores - purchased a fan and green vail and Isaac some hose, having been stockingless for some days  We reached Manchester about 1/2 past ten - unclear A? onto the street and made some purchases and

9
then to the Manchester Hotel to dine - after which set us at? the parlor with some very talkative ladies till carriage came to take us to the depot - at half past two - and soon Dunbarton's borng? hills appeared and we were welcomed home. Dear father, mother & Jenny there, but no George - sorry not to see him but all is right and best I know -
Wednesday - Sept 8 - Mr. Jameson and his scholars called this afternoon and some others - all seem good & kind -
Wednesday Sept 15 - This day left my dear home and dear friends for a new home in Illinois. O there was hope & fear, sadness & joy in my heart -  Capt ?/Mrs Brown?

10
Agnes were in last eve and T? B. came in this morn to say good by and leave a beautiful book mark her own loving handiwork -

Sept 17th Friday Sept, New-York at six this morning. Reached Troy about Eleven. Scenery all along the Hudson delightful but we hurried past it at the rate of forty miles per hour. the palisaedes on the west side look like the contisenors palace crowned with Evergreen with ivy climbing up all about it - and moss clinging to its sides. Farther up te river the highlands come in sight - steep cliffs on each side sometimes almost perpendicular. I would just begin to look and then what I wanted to see would be gone - gone, gone. I think it would be most glorious to sail up the river in a steamboat
Saturday  - 18. Had intended to stop in Troy last night but suddenly concluded to take the night train for Buffalo, and if possible save being out on Sabbath. reached Buffalo about nine and went immediately on board the Louisiana - lake smooth & still all day and all night-
19 reached Cleveland about four this sabbath morning nearly

12 
to get to Cleveland? by last eve but could not, to chh. in afternoon and evening  - heard Rev. Dr. Stedwell of Illinois Colggge and Rev. Dr. Carlisle.
American house our stopping place
Monday 20 - Mail two letters this morning one to Anna one home - Left Cleveland for Cincinnati about eleven - rode all day & till past eleven at night Dr. Stedwell & sister in company. Stopped at the Burnett house - Splendid house - all quiet and comfortable every accommodation one could desire.
Tuesday 21 Isaac went out this morning to the Levee & sent back a package a tracts English & German - purchased a melodeon and two pieces of music - $40,00 for instrument. I did not know how to thank him for being so good and kind. Was ever mortal so blessed as my unworthy self. new mercies every day and hour. Let me not forget the Giver of all good.
Read in Harper and Tracts gave some tracts to the chamber girl. Walked about with Isaac in the forenoon to the music store and in the Evening about the principal Streets. Some fine residences and some good specimens of ancient architecture, the churches, institutions etc. See back.

1 
Reached Bangor in the evening of July 6 - stopped at the Ur. Gumburn's saw Lucy and her husband- Eliab and a daughter of Almeida July 12 Sabbath at Bangor
July 15 - came to Milo to day - have seen our mother. Charles Albina with their two children, Almeida & little Lizz and James much pleased with all. How very kind is mt HEavenly Father to grant me so many Blessings and so much of happiness. 
Friday July 16 went to visit the Katadin Iron works. Eliab came Saturday. Delightful boat ride Sabbath. The dear, delicius silent " Sabbath  come again went to Foxcroft to church hear Mr. Parker - much interesting manner solemn and impressive
Monday - Lost part of our company Mr. & Mrs. Furber and Eliab were gone back to Bangor. 
Tuesday - walked by the river gathered many sweet flowers new varieties to me. some very rarely found.
Wednesday - went over to see Almeida

passed the afternoon very happily 2
made dress and apron for Little Lissie (mother ?)
Isaac sick at night, but made us all happy very suddenly, but getting well again.
Thursday another delightful walk by the river with I.
Friday 23 Helped about Almeida's dress - fitted lining etc.
Saturday - Sewed in the A.M. for Almeida. Afternoon read some - long sail up the river - sky  clouds magnificent Gazed on the still bright waters watched the shadows of the trees and flowers and fleecy clouds plucked the flowers while ? & landed by a fine little spring of excellent water clambouring up the bank after, I had cut away the blackberries and ? and seating us upon the grass unloaded our provisions box and regaled ourselves upon its contents - drinking the pure forest spring water.
Sabbath July 25 Mr. Follet - Baptist preached long & loud- from 1 Cor. 6.20 in forenoon and 1 Pet. 2.4.- P.M. some good especially in sermon. 
Monday -dull and rainy read Mary Lyon at night

3?
Read Mary Lyon forenoon Went to ride in afternoon, and to pick raspberries after supper.
wrote part of a letter to Emilia. 
25 Finished letter to E,ilia
29 wrote to George - sail on the river - little Charly went.
20 read 114 pages in "Mary Lyon" in forenoon knitted watch sop afternoon- began to fit my gingham dress wet to Almeida's for supper
Aug. 1 Sabbath went to Brownville to meeting - heard Mr. Sewall. Text in forenoon Gen. 6.5 Afternoon 1 Kings 22.8
Monday  - went to Brownville -called at Mr. Ryder's - took supper at the Brown's. saw Mrs. Greenleaf and Wilder from Illinois. Very pleasant ladies.
Tuesday delightful ride to Sebec - view of mountains Sugar Load . Was back just in season for dinner.
Wednesday wrote to Lucy

4
visitor? Almeda's - neck? chicken for Dinner. Anna & I pick raspberries for tea. Isaac gone to Foxcroft all day - so I could but half enjoy it.
Thursday - rain rain all the day - read "Mary Lyon" and sewed on my dress - finished it -
Friday - Wrote to Augustus - rainy forenoon - foggy, misty afternoon -  letter from home - feel somewhat disposed to be grieved and sad because my dear brother gone to Andover and I cannot see him - and Loch? and Schla? will friendship both be gone when I go home and I cannot even look at them - But I am glad enough that they are  all well, mother and all - blessings are all around me, and I cannot help being a happy, thankful child - even if all does not occur just as I seem to desire.
Saturday Aug 8? smudged out?  Sewing  reading knitting - no spenning an afternoon with Anna & Charley -
Sabbath Aug 8.  At home is? forever?   /See back/
